Here begins one of those long dialogues , where one person is represented as taking both sides of an argument . 
This rhetorical device , so wearisome to modern readers , is used by Chretien preferably when some sentiment or deep emotion is to be portrayed . 
Ovid may well have suggested the device , but Ovid never abuses it as does the more prolix mediaeval poet . 
For the part playing by the eyes in mediaeval love sophistry , see J. F. Hanford , The Debate of Heart and Eye in Modern Language Notes , xxvi . 
and H. R. Lang , The Eyes as Generators of Love . 
